At approximately 21:15 EST, Airport Operations Supervisor Ops 1 received a call from the Air Traffic Control Tower regarding bird remains that were seen on runway 29 by a departing aircraft. Ops 1 responded to the runway immediately to locate the remains of the bird. Upon arrival to the scene of the strike, Ops 1 was able to identify the bird remains to be that of a Juvenile Snowy Owl. The remains were found partially intact on runway 29 at taxiway D, approximately 20 feet to the north of the runway centerline. Following a runway inspection and removal of the remains,  Ops 1 confirmed with ATC that the previously departed Fed Ex aircraft reported seeing the remains of the bird on the runway, however, there was not an aircraft that reported to ATC of being struck by the Snowy Owl. NIGHT 2115.

ATCT reported to Ops 1 that the crew of AA flight 5326 reported seeing the remains on the runway as they exited runway 29 at taxiway F after landing. The crew of AA 5326 reported that they did not strike the bird, they only observed the remains on the runway as they exited. There are no further strike reports known at this time regarding an aircraft that struck the bird. Also, there has been no damage reported to Airport Operations at this time. REMARKS: Evidence of a strike was found during inspection between flights on the left wing of JBU1445 (EMB-190, N355JB, KBOS to KCLT).  Unknown if the inbound flight crew were aware of the strike, and unable to determine when/where the strike occurred.  The aircraft did incur a go-around at CLT before landing, but this was weather related, not strike related.  Remains were cleaned off of the aircraft by airline ground crews before CLT Airside Ops arrival, but a sample was able to be salvaged and has been sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  CLT Airside Ops was also not called by the airline prior to the aircraft departing for its next scheduled flight.  Because of this it is believed no damage was found.  Inspection of the arrival runway was also completed but no other remains/evidence was found. FOUND KCLT. NIGHT. 22R at BOS, 18R at CLT. Smithsonian Wildlife/Species Identification:Snowy owl (Bubo scandiacus)Smithsonian Wildlife Identification Comments:Species suggest strike occurred on takeoff from BOS. Possible duplicate of 2021-12-13-092527

1256L: During routine patrol, American Airlines 45 was observed striking a snowy owl on 04Rin between TWY Z and J. At approximately 1300L, wildlife supervisors advised ATC and requested clearance to enter 04R for carcass removal. Wildlife supervisor met the aircraft at Terminal 8 Gate 12, where the mechanic (G. Karras) was onsite. Snarge and remnants were observed on the nose cone and outer parts of the engine indicating an ingestion. Mechanic (G. Karras) was not able to confirm if it was a core ingestion, further inspection will be conducted. Extent of damage unknown at the time of reporting. As of 1800L, AA mechanic (G. Karras) confirmed ingestion into engine core. Aircraft placed out of service for further inspection.  AAL Air Safety stated:  Bird strike right side of aircraft during landing into right engine.  Damage found at 12 o'clock position aft of the outlet guide vanes (OGV). Bird remains were found the in precooler inlet duct & fan air valve on engine #2.  Four outlet guide vane (OGV) spacers were replaced. A borescope inspection of the engine revealed no engine damage. Time out of service: 3 days
